        </div>

        <p>Steven Universe also touches upon concepts of gender expression. The term gender expression refers to the ways in which individuals externally communicate their gender identity to others through things like clothing, voice, and other forms of appearance. Some individuals may not choose to match their gender expression to the &ldquo;typical&rdquo; norm for their gender identity. Jasper is presented as one of the main villains for the Crystal Gems to fight. She is a homeworld Gem who holds a major grudge against Rose Quartz/Steven. While Rebecca Sugar has confirmed that Jasper uses she/her pronouns, her gender expression is not what society associates with &ldquo;women&rdquo;. Jasper has a lower, rough voice as well as an extremely large and muscular body shape, nothing about her gender expression is &ldquo;feminine&rdquo;. Again, Steven and the team make no mention of this and the show never takes time to question whether it matters if her gender expression falls in line with the standards for her gender identity, Jasper is simply accepted as a pretty badass villain. </p>

        <p>Overall the show allows children to understand something as complex as gender by simply providing representation in a way that is not sexualized or criticized by others in the Steven Universe world.  </p>

